What Is a Decision? (How Humans Choose vs Computers)

Imagine you are standing in front of a shop that sells many ice cream flavors. Chocolate, vanilla, strawberry — you pause, think for a moment, and then choose one. That simple act is called a decision. A decision is just choosing one option while leaving the others behind. We make these choices all the time — what to eat, which road to take, when to stop talking and start listening. Most of the time, we don’t even realize we’re doing it, but decisions are the bridge between thinking about something and actually acting on it.

Now let’s see how a computer makes a decision. When a computer chooses something, it doesn’t pause and “think” like we do. It follows instructions. For example, a traffic light turns red when a timer ends, even if the road is empty. A calculator gives the same answer every time you type the same numbers. These are decisions too, but they work very differently. The computer isn’t asking “Is this a good idea?” — it’s simply following steps written by humans.

This is where humans and computers start to feel very different. Humans make decisions by using experience. If you’ve eaten ice cream before, you already know which flavor you like. If it starts raining, you decide to slow down or find shelter, even if no one taught you a rule for that exact moment. Your brain connects memories, feelings, and the situation in front of you. Computers struggle here. If a situation is new and not covered by their instructions, they don’t know what to do unless someone updates them.

To help computers handle more situations, we changed how we teach them. Instead of giving them strict instructions for every choice, we show them many examples. Over time, the computer starts to notice patterns, like “in situations like this, this choice usually works better.” This is similar to how a child learns. You don’t explain every rule of life — you let them try, make mistakes, and improve. The computer’s decisions slowly get better as it sees more examples and learns from feedback.

So here’s the key idea to remember. Humans make decisions by understanding situations and adapting, even when things are new. Computers make decisions by following instructions or patterns they’ve learned from past examples. They don’t truly understand the situation — they calculate the most likely choice. In the next part of this series, we’ll look even deeper at how choices turn into actions, and how learning helps machines improve their decisions over time.


